<HEADLINE>
FT  15 OCT 93 / International Company News: Sun Micro hits peak with Dollars
16.6m in first quarter
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SUN Microsystems reported record first-quarter revenues but the computer
workstation manufacturer failed to live up to earnings expectations.
Net earnings for the quarter were Dollars 16.6m, or 16 cents a share,
including a credit of about Dollars 6m from tax changes.
This compares with net income of Dollars 4.8m, or 5 cents in the same period
last year.
Wall Street analysts had been projecting income of about 26 cents per share.
Revenues rose 12 per cent to Dollars 960.5m from Dollars 855.9m in the first
quarter of the last fiscal year.
Strong growth in the US market as well as reduced costs helped to mitigate
continued weakness in several European markets, said Mr Kevin Melia, Sun's
chief financial officer. 'For the fourth consecutive quarter we have driven
down our operating expenses as a percentage of revenues compared with the
year-ago period,' said Mr Melia.
'For the second consecutive quarter this decrease in expenses more than
offset the expected decline in the gross margin percentage, and enabled us
to again grow operating income faster than revenues,' he said.
Earlier this week, top executives at Sun took a self-imposed pay cut of
about 30 per cent, saying that their compensation should be more closely
linked to the company's performance through stock options.
Sun's results were issued after the close of trading yesterday.
On Wall Street, Sun shares closed at Dollars 23, up from Wednesday's Dollars
21 5/8.
</TEXT>
