<HEADLINE>
FT  15 OCT 93 / International Company News: Apple turns in small profit as
revenues soar to record level
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
APPLE Computer reported a small profit for its fourth quarter as gross
margins on its personal computer products slid from more than 40 per cent to
about 26 per cent amid industry-wide price cutting.
Net income for the quarter was Dollars 2.7m , or 2 cents a share, down from
Dollars 97.6m, or 81 cents, in the same period last year. Revenues for the
quarter were Dollars 2.14bn, the highest level in the company's history and
up 21 per cent from Dollars 1.77bn in the fourth quarter of fiscal 1992.
To compensate for lower gross margins, in its third fiscal quarter Apple
announced a sweeping restructuring. As a result of these changes, fourth
quarter operating expenses were reduced by Dollars 80m or 13 per cent, the
company said.
'We have challenges ahead of us, but I believe we are beginning to turn the
corner,' said Mr Michael Spindler, president and chief executive.
'Our new prices for Macintosh computers . . . led to brisk sales and market
share gains during the quarter.'
For fiscal 1993, Apple's net income was Dollars 86.6m, or 73 cents a share,
down from Dollars 530.4m, or Dollars 4.33 a share, last year. The company
took a pre-tax charge against earnings of Dollars 321m in the third quarter.
Revenues rose to Dollars 7.98bn from Dollars 7.09bn in 1992.
</TEXT>
