<DATE>931015
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  15 OCT 93 / International Company News: Wall Street welcomes Bell-TCI
merger
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
SHARES in Bell Atlantic, the US regional telephone group, soared to record
levels yester day as Wall Street continued to register its delight over
Bell's bid for Tele-Communications Inc, the biggest US cable television
company.
Bell Atlantic closed up Dollars 1 3/4 at Dollars 67 5/8 - on top of a
Dollars 5 7/8 rise on Wednesday when the deal was announced. TCI's A shares
closed at Dollars 32 7/8 , up Dollars 1 1/2 , on top of Wednesday's Dollars
3 rise.
It is unusual for the shares of both bidding and target company to rise by
such a large amount following the announcement of a deal. Wall Street likes
the industrial logic, does not feel Bell Atlantic is paying an excessive
premium for TCI, and is relieved that the deal is a stock swap, which does
not involve the issuance of additional debt.
The terms of the deal are complex and depend in part on just how much Bell
Atlantic is allowed to buy of TCI and of Liberty Media, a spun-off
programming subsidiary of TCI which the cable company is in the process of
re-acquiring.
It could experience delays in acquiring TCI's and Liberty's programming
assets, since these use the long-distance phone network and Bell Atlantic
will need a court waiver from regulations barring the Baby Bell companies
from the long-distance business.
It also plans to sell or spin off TCI's cable service operations, which
overlap with the area where it provides telephone services, since to acquire
them would be illegal.
Bell Atlantic is to pay 11.75 annualised cash flow for the cable properties
it is buying, while the programming and other assets would be valued at
public market value at closing.
Bell Atlantic will accomplish the merger by issuing new Class B common
stock, valued at Dollars 54 each, which is not expected to pay dividends for
five years. After that, it would pay the same dividend as Bell Atlantic's
current common stock, to be renamed Class A.
The class B stock would be convertible into class A stock after five years.
There would be a 10 per cent premium for holders of TCI's class B shares
(each of which command 10 votes) over class A shareholders.
The two companies estimate that if the acquisition of the cable assets were
completed now, Bell Atlantic would issue some 220m class B shares, worth
Dollars 11.8bn, or some Dollars 19 a TCI A share, and it would also assume
some Dollars 9.6bn of debt. The holder of each TCI A-share would receive
around 0.35 of a Bell Atlantic share. However, if the deal is not completed
until the end of next year, this could rise to 0.40 and the value of the
deal to some Dollars 13bn.
If Bell Atlantic was permitted to buy all of the Liberty-TCI assets it wants
when the deal closes, it estimates that each TCI-LIberty class A shareholder
would receive around 0.65 of class B Bell Atlantic share, pushing the total
value of the deal to Dollars 22bn to Dollars 23bn, and the value of each TCI
A share to around Dollars 35.
Bell Atlantic said it expected earnings per share dilution in the first year
after closing of around 30 per cent to 35 per cent from the initial cable
properties. Growth in earnings per share is expected to be well above 10 per
cent a year for the five-year period after closing the deal.
If there are delays in the transfer of the programming assets, Bell Atlantic
will distribute these, along with the in-region cable assets, to
shareholders in TCI-Liberty in the form of a separately traded company.
</TEXT>
