<HEADLINE>
FT  15 OCT 93 / International Company News: Mexico cuts tax on interest for
foreign loans
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAMIAN FRASER and STEPHEN FIDLER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MEXICO CITY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Mexican government is cutting the tax that domestic companies pay on
their interest on foreign bank loans. This is expected to reduce their cost
of funding in foreign currencies.
The government plans to reduce, initially for a two-year period, the
withholding tax to 4.9 per cent, from 15 per cent, on their interest on bank
loans. This will cut the cost of foreign bank funding by one-tenth.
The tax reduction is expected to increase capital flows into Mexico.
It may also put pressure on Mexican banks to lower their interest rates.
The move will not affect bonds issued by Mexican companies, which are exempt
from the tax.
</TEXT>
