<HEADLINE>
FT  15 OCT 93 / International Company News: Ericsson joins Inmarsat
consortium
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DANIEL GREEN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
ERICSSON, the Swedish telecommunications manufacturer, has thrown its weight
behind Inmarsat, a 71-nation satellite operator, in the race to create a
global mobile telecommunications network.
The link has created the biggest potential competitor yet to rival a Dollars
3.4bn scheme proposed by US company Motorola.
Both organisations plan to launch a series of telecommunications satellites
by the end of the decade which would allow a single portable telephone to be
operated anywhere in the world.
Mr Kurt Hellstrom, the president of Ericsson Radio Systems, said yesterday
that he would work 'with Inmarsat to develop the necessary infrastructure'
for the network so that a portable telephone could switch automatically
between a cellular network and a satellite link.
Ericsson and Motorola are two of the world's biggest companies involved in
building cellular telephone networks and handsets. Inmarsat is a
co-operative established in 1979 to provide satellite communications for
ships. Since then it has moved into new markets for emergency services and
the media.
Mr Hellstrom said that Ericsson preferred to join forces with Inmarsat over
Motorola because of Inmarsat's 'open system' plan which would allow any
manufacturer to make telephones for the network.
The Inmarsat scheme, called Project 21, faces a struggle to catch up with
Motorola's plan, called Iridium. Companies from North and South America,
Europe and Asia have already agreed to provide Motorola's consortium with
Dollars 100m in cash and promised another Dollars 700m as the first stage in
financing Iridium.
Normally, Inmarsat would have to turn to its owners, such as Comsat in the
US and European telecommunications organisations like BT and France Telecom,
to contribute to the capital cost of a network of satellites.
But earlier this week, Inmarsat said it would reorganise to become more like
the private sector with which it is increasingly competing. It will propose
next year that its 71 members be allowed to buy and sell stakes in Inmarsat.
Mr Olof Lundberg, director general of Inmarsat said: 'If we are going to
join the commercial world, we need a new set of attitudes.'
He said that Inmarsat would have to move closer to mass markets and learn
about marketing and bring products and services quickly to the market place.
</TEXT>
