FT  15 OCT 93 / International Company News: Santander acquires City property
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TOM BURNS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GRUPO SANTANDER, the Spanish banking and financial services holding, aims to
spend up to Pounds 100m (Dollars 151m) on City of London property as part of
a strategy to diversify its business interests and build up profit centres
outside Spain.
Santander said yesterday it had spent some Pounds 18m to acquire D'Arcy
House at 146 Queen Victoria Street and a further Pounds 13.75m to buy 1
Bishopsgate, the London headquarters of Fidelity Bank. It is in the final
stages of purchasing a third property close to St Paul's Cathedral for about
Pounds 20m.
A spokesman for the group said acquisitions, which mark Santander's first
move into real estate, would continue in the City and with an investment
ceiling of Pounds 100m. 'London has been preferred to other centres because
of the profitability of its property market,' he said.
Santander's business diversification strategy was underlined last month when
it announced a Pounds 400m joint venture with British Telecommunications to
develop data transmission services in Spain.
Mr Emilio Botin, the Santander chairman, told shareholders earlier this year
that he aimed to increase the group's presence abroad and wished to raise
the proportion of the group's net profits earned outside Spain from a
present level of just over 30 per cent to 50 per cent.
