<HEADLINE>
FT  15 OCT 93 / Prices squeeze deflates Smurfit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PAUL TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JEFFERSON Smurfit, the Irish paper and packaging group with operations
throughout Europe and the Americas, yesterday reported a 16 per cent decline
in interim pre-tax profits which it blamed on 'continuing price erosion' and
some volume reductions.
Pre-tax profits fell from IPounds 60.3m (Pounds 57.9m) to IPounds 50.7m in
the six months to July 31. Sales rose from IPounds 654m to IPounds 749.5m,
reflecting the inclusion of UK Corrugated, Cundell and Irish Paper Products
for the first time.
Earnings per share dropped by 18.7 per cent to 7.4p (9.1p) but the directors
declared an unchanged interim dividend of 1.2306p. The shares slipped 8p to
close at 214p.
Mr Michael Smurfit, chairman, said the results 'continue to reflect both the
severity of the current world recession and the state of our industry'.
Trading profits dropped to IPounds 39.5m, from IPounds 59.3m, but the
decline was partly offset by a quadrupling of net interest receipts to
IPounds 11.6m. Since the year-end, net cash declined from IPounds 150m to
IPounds 24m, aggravated by currency devaluation.
Mr Ray Curran, chief financial officer, said that Latin America had again
been the 'mainstay'. Operating profits there slipped to IPounds 28.5m
(IPounds 30.6m) but the region increased its share of overall profits from
53 to 73 per cent.
The deepening recession in continental Europe resulted in lost volumes in
all operations with prices deteriorating as the group struggled to maintain
market share. Sales fell by 13 per cent and profits dropped by 41 per cent
to IPounds 9.67m.
The newly combined Ireland/UK region had a difficult first half mainly
because of a 'disappointing performance' by the UK print and carton
companies. Corrugated volumes in the UK were higher but that was more than
offset by lower prices. Despite a slight profit increase in Ireland, the
combined region posted a 20 per cent decline in operating profits to IPounds
11.5m.
JSC/CCA, the US associate, suffered from the sluggish economy and excessive
paperboard inventories, while improving newsprint demand had yet to lift
prices. Losses attributable to the US operations increased from IPounds
4.06m to IPounds 10.7m.
The US associate has announced plans for a Dollars 150m (Dollars 100m after
tax) rationalisation programme which is likely to result in the group taking
an IPounds 25m exceptional charge.
Lex, Page 22
</TEXT>
