<HEADLINE>
FT  15 OCT 93 / Write-downsat ADT and Attwoods hit Laidlaw
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BERNARD SIMON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TORONTO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
LAIDLAW, the North American waste services and transport operator, has
cleared the way for the disposal or rationalisation of its interests in ADT,
the international security and vehicle auction group, and Attwoods, the
UK-based waste services company.
The group has sharply written down the carrying value of its investments in
the two companies.
The write-down of the 24 per cent stake in ADT and the 35 per cent interest
in Attwoods totalled USDollars 243.8m (Pounds 161.4m). Laidlaw is the
largest single shareholder in both companies.
The moves were part of a house-cleaning exercise which appears to signal a
more active role in Laidlaw's affairs by its Montreal-based controlling
shareholder, Canadian Pacific.
Laidlaw also named Mr Jim Bullock as chief executive to replace Mr Donald
Jackson, who was asked to resign last week. Mr Bullock was formerly
president of Cadillac Fairview, a large Toronto-based property developer.
The write-downs pushed Laidlaw to a loss of USDollars 334.9m, or Dollars
1.21 a share, in the fourth quarter to August 31, compared with net income
of Dollars 24.9m, or 9 cents a share, a year earlier.
Revenues rose 10 per cent to Dollars 467.5m but income from continuing
operations dipped to Dollars 3.9m from Dollars 24.9m.
Laidlaw also set aside Dollars 105m to cover closures, delays and falling
values at several landfill and hazardous waste facilities in the US and
Canada.
CP tries to get to grips with Laidlaw legacy, Page 29
</TEXT>
