<HEADLINE>
FT  15 OCT 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICIA MORISON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Two of the very best English gardens, romantic Kiftsgate Court in
Gloucestershire and Esther Merton's rectory in Berkshire, bring to a close
An English Woman's Garden (BBC 2, 8.30). Mrs Merton's garden is full of
marvellous plants and is not widely known, so tonight's programme should not
be missed.
A new comedy series, Demob (ITV, 9.00) brings Griff Rhys Jones and Martin
Clunes together as soldiers newly back in Civvy Street. They team up and
start at the bottom of the ladder as comedians in Liverpool.
Odd one out of the week is The Living Soap (BBC 2, 7.15), the
fly-on-the-wall documentary about the lives of six very assorted students
studying at Manchester University. They share a house procured for them by
the BBC - hundreds of students applied for the job. The six are, quite
rightly, paid for appearing in the series, which will help their measly
grants stretch a little further.
Clive Anderson Talks Back (C4, 10.30), is the first of another series of the
long-running chat show - guests are David Frost and Gore Vidal.
</TEXT>
