<TEXT>
LORD Chalfont, chairman of the Radio Authority, last night attacked the BBC
for deciding to go ahead with a news and sports radio network in place of
Radio 5 - and pre-empting next year's new national commercial channel.
'If the BBC is able to pre-empt a format which certainly could be provided
by the commercial sector at no extra cost to the TV licence fee payer and
without narrowing listener choice, how can we, in the independent sector, be
expected to make rational plans for broadening listener choice in the
future?' he asked.
Lord Chalfont was speaking at a dinner in London to mark the 20th
anniversary of UK commercial radio, which the Radio Authority regulates.
Lord Chalfont said the BBC should have to stick to performance promises. 'No
independent radio station can change its format or its promise of
performance unless the change can be shown not to narrow the range of
programmes available,' he added.
