<HEADLINE>
FT  15 OCT 93 / Consumer confidence at four-year high
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONSUMER confidence in the third quarter was at its highest level for more
than four years, according to a survey published yesterday which suggests
the recovery is becoming better established.
The rise in consumer spending, which has been a big factor behind the past
year's upturn, is 'increasingly robust' with southern England leading the
way, says the report by Business Strategies, an economic consultancy, and
the Gallup market research group.
Low interest rates, reduced unemployment and signs of a better economic
climate are boosting people's willingness to spend, apparently offsetting
gloomy news elsewhere in the economy.
Negative factors are that many people are worried about the Pounds 6.8bn of
higher taxes announced for the next financial year. Also, more individuals
than earlier in the year expect inflationary pressures to rise over the next
few months.
The index of consumer confidence based on answers to questions put to 6,000
people throughout Britain gave a figure of 16 in the third quarter of this
year, up from 11 in the second quarter and 4 in the first quarter. The last
time it was higher was in the first three months of 1989.
Optimism about the economic climate is highest in south-east England - in
spite of this region having suffered particularly badly during the recession
in terms of unemployment and a fall in house prices.
According to estimates by Business Strategies, consumer spending in
south-east England outside London increased by 1.9 per cent in the year to
the third quarter, higher than the figure for Britain as a whole of 1.6 per
cent.
Other regions with particularly high rises in consumer spending over this
period were south-west England, East Anglia and north-west England. These
saw increases of 2.8 per cent, 2 per cent and 1.9 per cent respectively.
Mr David Fell, a director of Business Strategies, said all regions were
sharing in the general rise in consumer confidence. However, optimism could
still slip back, for example in the event of the government announcing a
further large increase in taxation for 1994-95 in next month's Budget.
</TEXT>
