<HEADLINE>
FT  15 OCT 93 / Accountant fined by regulators
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A PARTNER in the insolvency division of Coopers &amp; Lybrand, the UK's largest
accountancy firm, has been reprimanded by his regulatory body for breaches
of the law and of professional guidelines.
Mr Adrian Stanway, based in Coopers' London office, was fined Pounds 3,500
and ordered to pay Pounds 1,750 in costs by the professional conduct
committee of the Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales.
The action was brought in relation to his work as liquidator to JDC Stokes
Civil Engineering between February 1990 and October last year.
At a meeting held in August, details of which have just been made public,
the disciplinary committee ruled that Mr Stanway failed to hold an annual
creditors' meeting in accordance with Section 105 of the Insolvency Act
1986.
It also ruled that he had breached the minimum standard of insolvency
practice resulting in delays and unanswered correspondence from a creditor.
Mr Stanway admitted the faults, arguing that although he had been partner in
charge of the case, he had no personal control over the company's file and
that there had been a systems breakdown and human error in the office.
Coopers said it had taken disciplinary action against a manager and other
staff in its Southampton office in connection with the case. It is believed
Coopers will pay Mr Stanway's fine and plans no action against him. In
separate proceedings announced yesterday, Mr Frank Shannon, a former finance
director of Nissan UK, was excluded from membership of the institute. He was
sentenced to three years imprisonment in July after he admitted cheating the
Inland Revenue.
</TEXT>
