FT  15 OCT 93 / Policing insider dealing
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TIM BURT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A CENTRAL enforcement agency should be created to police insider dealing, a
seminar of stockbrokers and company finance directors was told yesterday,
Tim Burt writes.
The agency would also clarify guidelines on price sensitive information,
said Mr Michael Ashe, a barrister and expert on insider dealing. It would
combine the work of the Crown Prosecution Service, and the Securities and
Investment Board and other self-regulating organisations.
Mr Ashe's call was backed by Mr Richard Lines, investigations manager at the
Stock Exchange's surveillance department, who agreed there was a need for
such an agency.
Speaking at a seminar in Birmingham, Mr Ashe said: 'There has been a problem
with enforcement in the securities industry. It's time to have a single
agency.'
