<HEADLINE>
FT  15 OCT 93 / World Cup loss could cost Pounds 35m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AFTER the national side lost 2-0 to The Netherlands on Wednesday night,
English football could lose up to Pounds 20m if Graham Taylor's team fails
to qualify for next year's World Cup finals in the US, Diane Summers writes.
Failure would cost the travel industry an estimated Pounds 15m, and there
would also be losses in publishing and broadcasting, gaming and to companies
associated with football merchandising.
Mr Trevor Phillips, the Football Association's commercial director, said the
FA would forgo between Pounds 3m and Pounds 4m in receipts and as much as
Pounds 20m could be lost to football as a whole, including a drop in takings
on gates during the season after the cup.
Greaves Travel, FA official travel agent, said that reductions in bookings
to the US next year would mean a loss of up to Pounds 15m for the travel
industry as a whole.
However, Mr Michael Myers, marketing director, said that inquiries from the
corporate market was holding up and there could actually be a boost to
family holidays in the US. 'Families can now go knowing they won't be mixed
up with that kind of supporter,' he said.
American Airlines, official airline to the World Cup, is suspending
television and press advertising because of the negative association with
the competition. It was 'deemed to be insensitive in the short term' to
advertise, said the airline, although it did not plan to cut its promotion
budgets overall.
</TEXT>
