<HEADLINE>
FT  15 OCT 93 / IBM offshoot in mainframe drive
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE UK subsidiary of International Business Machines, the world's largest
computer manufacturer, is spending Pounds 3m over the next 18 months on a
campaign to persuade top executives that mainframe computers have a future.
Sales of mainframes, costing Pounds 1m or more, have been steadily declining
for years. IBM UK has been particularly hard hit, losing more than Pounds
600m in 1992. Mr Arthur Parker, director of the UK company's mainframe
division, said the decline in mainframe revenues had been halted. IBM's
profitability depends, however, on customers finding new uses for
mainframes.
The campaign aims to persuade executives that mainframes have a role in
future systems.
A survey, commissioned by IBM and carried out by Cranfield School of
Management, concludes that chief executives believe mainframes are essential
but unexciting. It says: 'Chief executives feel far less intimidated by
information technology than they used to. As a result, they demand more from
their systems, want commercial solutions, not 'products' and want the focus
set firmly on end users.'
Companies have recently been buying networks of smaller computers, which may
cost more to run, rather than mainframes.
No Man is an Island. From Emma Silver at IBM on 0345-898898. Pounds 15.
</TEXT>
