<HEADLINE>
FT  15 OCT 93 / Whistle-blowers win friendly ear
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD DONKIN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EMPLOYEES worried about fraud or malpractice in the workplace have been
offered legal advice from a new charity. The organisation believes it could
help expose corporate frauds or avert disasters by advising
'whistle-blowers' in the workplace.
Public Concern at Work, which was launched yesterday, is offering advice for
employees worried about being victimised if they take concerns to their
employers. The group hopes that its work will help alert companies or
regulators to problems much earlier.
Sir Gordon Borrie, former director-general of fair trading and chairman of
the charity's trustees, said it would provide confidential legal advice
which would be protected by lawyer-client privilege.
He said: 'Time and again official inquiries into scandals, disasters and
tragedies show they could have been avoided if employees had spoken up in
time, or if those in charge had addressed the concerns of staff when they
were raised.'
He cited the multi-billion dollar fraud at the Bank of Credit and Commerce
International, The Herald of Free Enterprise ferry disaster and the
Leicestershire child abuse case involving Mr Frank Beck, the children's
homes director, as cases which might have been avoided had the concerns of
employees been recognised.
Sir Gordon stressed that clients would 'remain in the driving seat' and the
charity would advise them of their legal positions and the most effective
way of raising an issue.
The charity, he said, 'should make it less likely that employees will turn a
blind eye to serious malpractice and more likely that employers will be able
to address real problems before damage is done'.
The organisation, which will also provide advice and research reports for
employers, arose out of research by Ms Marlene Winfield, one of the
trustees, whose book, Minding Your Own Business, advocated the role of
whistle-blowers.
She said that of 53 British companies asked, only two had a fixed procedure
that assured employees of either confidentiality or protection against
retaliation. Yet most had felt that there were circumstances where
whistle-blowing would be justified.
'The gap between belief and practice was yawning, and still is,' she said.
'Speak to the boss and possibly lose your job, your pension, your mortgage,
the trust of your colleagues.'
</TEXT>
