<HEADLINE>
FT  15 OCT 93 / Engineering employers hit at Treasury
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW BAXTER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE ENGINEERING Employ-ers Federation yesterday accused the Treasury of
being 'isolated from the real world' of manufacturing, and warned that the
recovery in engineering output had halted.
The gloomy assessment of the sector's prospects - including a prediction of
a further 60,000 job losses - underlined the severity of the recession in
continental European export markets, and confirmed the message of falling
manufacturing output contained in official figures on Tuesday.
The federation said engineering output is not expected to pick up again
before next spring. Mr Ian Thompson, economic adviser, said there were no
prospects of a strong recovery in west European markets until 1995.
The forecast prompted an outspoken attack on the Treasury by Mr Neil
Johnson, director-general of the federation, who was worried not only by the
short-term outlook but by the long-term future of the engineering sector.
Mr Johnson said the federation still had high hopes for Mr Kenneth Clarke,
the chancellor. 'But I fear the Treasury may be trapping him, as it has
trapped so many of his predecessors,' he said.
Treasury officials were clever, perhaps too clever, he said. But they were
isolated from the real world and 'totally unspoilt by failure'.
'They cannot sail serenely on, seeing what they want to see, understanding
what they want to understand, and dismissing we little wealth-creating folk
with a gentle, patrician smile,' he added.
Underlying Mr Johnson's attack is the federation's belief that the UK does
not have a broad enough manufacturing base to satisfy domestic demand and
exports - especially when demand in continental markets recovers.
He said that if Mr Clarke was serious about boosting the UK's manufacturing
base, he should change the UK's system of capital allowances for industry,
which is 'biased against investment'. The federation believes UK gross
domestic product will grow by little more than 2 per cent next year. This
compares with a consensus among City and economic analysts of 3 per cent.
European recession and the continuing squeeze on costs because of global
competition would cause the 60,000 further job cuts in the next 12 months.
Employment in the sector has already fallen by 410,000 to 1.69m since the
first half of 1990.
Autumn 1993 Engineering Economic Trends. Despatch Department, EEF, Broadway
House, Tothill Street, London SW1H 9NQ. Pounds 35 (free to members).
