<HEADLINE>
FT  15 OCT 93 / Streamlined school tests published
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
REPLACEMENTS for the national curriculum tests that were boycotted this year
by teachers' unions were published yesterday to a divided reaction from
teachers.
The new tests for 14-year-olds are drastically altered from last year,
accommodating complaints about the workload they created for teachers and
attacks on their educational validity.
Mr Chris Woodhead, chief executive of the Schools Curriculum and Assessment
Authority, which has replaced the National Curriculum Council and the
Schools Examination and Assessment Council, said the tests were 'strong and
rigorous'.
The tests have been streamlined, with English reduced from three papers
lasting four hours to two lasting two hours and 45 minutes. Mathematics and
science are both reduced from three one-hour papers to two papers of one
hour.
According to the Department for Education, the tests confirm the policy of
slimming down the curriculum.
Mr Doug McAvoy, general secretary of the National Union of Teachers, said:
'The boycott remains in place. The government has regularly produced
estimates of the time the assessment and testing will take. It has always
been wrong.'
The Association of Teachers and Lecturers was more positive. Ms Gillian
Wood, assistant general secretary, gave the tests 'a broad welcome'.
</TEXT>
