<HEADLINE>
FT  15 OCT 93 / EC to seek unity on social policy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Labour Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE European Commission wants to do all it can to end Britain's isolation
from the rest of the EC on social policy.
That was the message from Mr Padraig Flynn, EC social affairs commissioner,
to a Confederation of British Industry conference in London yesterday.
'I believe we must continue to seek to progress social policy measures among
the 12 together,' he told his business audience. 'The social protocol of the
Maastricht treaty will be for the commission an instrument of last resort.'
Under the deal negotiated by Mr John Major, the prime minister, Britain can
opt out of social regulations that the other 11 Community states may
introduce in the future.
But Mr Flynn warned the British government that the EC would go ahead with
its proposed works council directive without Britain's involvement if
European employers and trade union organisations failed to reach agreement
within nine months on alternative non-legal information and consultation
procedures for workers in European trans-national companies.
In contrast, Mr Michael Forsyth, the employment minister, told the CBI that
it was 'quite wrong for the Community to go ahead with a directive on which
there was total dis-agreement between Europe's employers and unions'.
</TEXT>
