<DATELINE>
   LILONGWE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
OPPOSITION leaders in Malawi yesterday gave qualified approval to the
appointment of a three-man presidential council to take executive authority.
The appointment appears to mark the effective end of the rule of President
Hastings Banda, who is in South Africa recovering from a brain operation
carried out 10 days ago.
Mr Gwanda Chakuamba, appointed secretary-general of the ruling Malawi
Congress party only last week, heads the council, whose other two members
are Mr John Tembo and Mr Robson Chirwa, both cabinet ministers.
Spokesmen for opposition parties represented on a National Consultative
Council (NCC), negotiating an election timetable and procedure with the
government, have supported the decision to form a presidential council as a
necessary interim measure.
But they claim that the NCC has an agreement with the government according
to which the presidential council will reconvene parliament within seven
days, and amend the constitution to allow a neutral, caretaker president,
with limited powers, to hold office until elections in May.
Hospital reports say Dr Banda's progress is satisfactory.
