<HEADLINE>
FT  15 OCT 93 / Bank of Spain cuts interest rate to 9.5%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER BRUCE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   MADRID
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE BANK of Spain yesterday cut its benchmark interest rate half a
percentage point to 9.5 per cent, the lowest since 1978, following the
success of efforts on Wednesday by the minority socialist government of
Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez to secure safe passage for its tight 1994
budget.
Finance ministry officials said the Bank of Spain's move, quickly followed
by base rate cuts by Spain's big commercial banks, also reflected
satisfaction with inflation figures for September and a promise on Wednesday
by trade unions to continue negotiating a three-year wage moderation pact
with the government.
The government and its main partner in parliament, the ruling Catalan CiU,
announced they had reached agreement over the budget which would allow the
Catalans to vote in favour of its passage.
A small grouping of independent Canary Island MPs also said they would vote
for the budget and its success is now all but assured. That, in turn,
virtually ensures the survival of the government for the next year.
The Catalans had threatened not to support the budget, which cuts
non-interest spending and imposes, for the first time, taxes on unemployment
benefits, largely in an effort to force the central government to speed the
transfer of political and fiscal powers to Catalonia.
The socialists, nevertheless, appear to have come away from this clash the
winners. They have only had to fulfil an old promise to allow Catalonia and
other regions to spend 15 per cent of the income taxes raised by the central
government in their territories.
Subsequent negotiations and suggestionsthat they might fail allowed the
Catalans to claim that they had, in fact, wrestled away hard-won
concessions.
The CiU is unlikely in the foreseeable future to want to see the collapse of
the government of Mr Gonzalez.
Political observers in Madrid suggest that while the socialists remain a
parliamentary minority, an artificial tension with the Catalans is likely to
become the hallmark of Spanish politics as the CiU struggles to build up
nationalist support in Catalonia.
Political theatrics aside, the open declaration of support for the budget by
the CiU on Wednesday gives Mr Gonzalez a badly-needed breathing space.
It is unlikely he will now be seriously troubled in parliament until the
next budget in a year's time.
</TEXT>
