<HEADLINE>
FT  15 OCT 93 / Senior defence posts face Treasury threat
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE TREASURY is targeting senior Ministry of Defence staff and officers in
the armed forces as part of the drive to meet public spending targets for
the next three years.
Ministers believe planned cuts at this level are not proceeding quickly
enough.
They are understood to be taking a tough line in the face of MoD arguments
that a root and branch management reform has made it necessary to retain a
high proportion of senior staff while cutting junior ranks.
According to official figures, the number of officers employed by the MoD
fell by just 1.6 per cent between 1980 and 1992, while the number of army
privates and those of equivalent rank dropped by more than a quarter.
Talks aimed at setting departmental budgets until 1996-97 continued
yesterday morning in the cabinet's so-called EDX committee, with ministers
confident a settlement will be reached, as planned, by the end of this
month.
Some relatively low-spending departments, including the Foreign Office, are
understood to be close to settling. The tightest squeeze is being imposed in
the later years.
The focus on MoD staffing comes as senior Tory backbenchers are preparing to
use next week's two-day defence debate in the Commons to mount a rearguard
action against the threat of further defence cuts.
Mr Malcolm Rifkind, the defence secretary, has demanded a full-scale review
of Britain's armed forces if the Treasury refuses to drop its demands for
further cuts.
But a former armed forces minister last night called for a reduction in
troop levels in Northern Ireland, saying the deployment of British soldiers
in other countries had been limited because of the commitment to the
province.
The MoD argues that if the number of senior staff had been trimmed more
quickly, it would have been harder to implement its New Management Strategy
 -introduced in 1991 - under which responsibility for many functions is
being delegated away from the centre.
It says that if agreed targets for efficiency improvements are met, its mix
of staff should be for it to decide and not the Treasury. In 1991/92, the
last year for which figures are available, the department exceeded its
target by Pounds 44m or 22 per cent. Some MoD advisers acknowledge that
significant cuts at senior and middle-management level should be feasible
within a few years, once the reforms implemented under NMS have bedded down.
While a drive to encourage early retirement in senior MoD ranks could help
the government achieve the control totals under negotiation, it will be of
less assistance in reducing the proportion of Britain's gross domestic
product accounted for by public spending. This is because the pensions of
former MoD employees no longer count towards the control total but are part
of general government expenditure.
</TEXT>
<XX>
