<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 93 / International Company News: Turnround at First Chicago
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FIRST Chicago reported a record profit of Dollars 284m for the third quarter
yesterday as the company rebounded strongly from the Dollars 372m loss
incurred in the same period last year.
The mid-western banking group, the 13th-largest in the US, fell deep into
the red in 1992 after it took a Dollars 625m special provision to cover
credit losses related to the disposal of problem property assets.
With the bulk of the asset disposal programme over, First Chicago attributed
its latest improvement to strong contributions from all its main business
lines, particularly proprietary trading and venture capital.
The bank reported earnings of Dollars 117m from its venture capital
business, from virtually nothing in the same quarter a year ago.
Earnings from the trading of primarily interest rate options, swaps and
foreign exchange totalled Dollars 77m, the second best quarterly trading
performance in the bank's history.
Non-interest income was also boosted by continued growth in First Chicago's
credit card business, where fee revenues rose to Dollars 186.7m, up from
Dollars 138.6m a year ago, as total managed receivables grew by 23 per cent
to Dollars 9.6bn.
Net interest income was Dollars 341m in the quarter, up from Dollars 294m in
the same period of 1992 as the bank's loan assets shrank 10 per cent to
Dollars 21.6bn.
The bank's shares rose Dollars  5/8 to close at Dollars 50 on the New York
Stock Exchange yesterday.
</TEXT>
