<HEADLINE>
FT  14 OCT 93 / International Company News: Earnings at Weyerhaeuser fall
38% amid depressed conditions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANK MCGURTY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
WEYERHAEUSER, the US forest products group, yesterday said its third-quarter
earnings had fallen by 38 per cent, as a sharp decline in paper and pulp
prices offset a strong performance by its timber business.
The company, the world's largest private owner of softwood timber, linked
its overall performance to depressed conditions in the North American pulp
and paper industry. In this segment, profits were Dollars 2.5m, a sharp drop
from last year's Dollars 61.2m.
Prices for most paper and pulp products had fallen about 20 per cent from
1992 levels, the company said. In addition, it had curtailed production
levels at some mills because of soft market conditions.
Net income for the 13 weeks to September 26 was Dollars 66.6m, or 32 cents a
share, compared with Dollars 107.2m, or 53 cents, in the third quarter of
1992, which was a period of robust growth for the company.
Revenues slipped 5 per cent to Dollars 2.22bn, from Dollars 2.35bn a year
earlier.
Excluding special factors, however, the decline in earnings was marginal.
The 1993 results included a charge of 10 cents a share to provide for
changes in the federal corporate tax rate enacted this summer. Last year's
figure, meanwhile, reflected a one-time gain of 8 cents a share following
the partial settlement of tax refund dispute.
By contrast, Weyerhaeuser's timberlands and wood products division continued
to improve. Operating earnings climbed to Dollars 165.8m, against Dollars
103m last time, as supply shortages lifted prices for logs and lumber. Sales
volume for most products also surpassed year-earlier levels.
Weyerhaeuser's property and financial services operations earned Dollars
11.2m in the quarter, compared with Dollars 27.3m last time. The decline in
part reflects the sale earlier this year of GNA Corp, a mutual fund
business.
Although the results were in line with most analysts' expectations, the
announcement was followed by a dip in Weyerhaeuser's shares. By midday, the
stock was down Dollars  7/8 at Dollars 39.
</TEXT>
